Durban -  The South African Association for Marine Biological Research (SAAMBR) is ecstatic about turtle hatching season - a time when the beaches of northern KwaZulu-Natal comes alive with Leatherback and Loggerhead turtle hatchlings, all desperately scrabbling down to the sea. Once at sea they are usually carried offshore in the ocean currents. The survival of these tiny turtles is generally very low, but if they wash up on a beach there are some things that we can do to can help them. Here’s what to do if you find one:   Turtles are a protected species and a special permit or permission is required to have one in your possession. Daily News